  "quality": "research",
  "script_type": "alphabet",
  "notes": "Brazilian Portuguese. Based directly on late Old Portuguese diaspora phonology. Key innovations: (1) Loss of coda R (ɾ→∅; later urban ɦ/ʁ in some dialects). (2) Coda sibilants remain alveolar (s, z), no universal palato-alveolar outcome. (3) L-vocalisation (l→w) strong and categorical in coda. (4) Palatalisation of /t, d/ > [t͡ʃ, d͡ʒ] before /i/. (5) Much weaker vowel reduction; loss of ɨ. (6) Final /e/→/i/ and /o/→/u/. (7) /rr/ always uvular. (8) Nasal vowel system preserved but with characteristic BR realisation.",
